<TITLE> JS committees reformed to induct women MPs </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, July 07 (bdnews24.com)Twenty parliamentary standing committees were reconstituted on Tuesday to induct women MPs that were elected to reserved seats. Chief whip Abdus Shahid told parliament the remainder of the 47 committees would be similarly reformed over the next few days. The treasury bench for the first time in Bangladesh's parliamentary history formed all 47 standing committees during the first session11 parliamentary affairs committees and 36 committees on different ministries, with representatives of the main opposition BNP made chairmen in some cases as another first. The 45 women MPs elected to reserved seats took their places in the House in the last half of the first session, after the committees were formed. Parliament elected the reconstituted committees by voice vote on Tuesday with chief whip Shahid proposing their passage. The reformed committees include the Rules of Procedure Committee, Petition Committee, Private Members' Bills and Private Members' Resolutions, Library Committee, Public Accounts Committee, Public Undertaking Committee, Government Assurance Committee. The others are the parliamentary standing committees on the defence ministry, housing and public works ministry, standing committee on local government ministry, foreign ministry, establishment ministry, textile and jute ministry, planning ministry, industries ministry, health and family welfare ministry, women and children affairs ministry, expatriates' welfare and overseas employment ministry, agriculture ministry and fisheries and livestock ministry. Speaker Abdul Hamid heads the committee on rules of procedure. Its other members are: chief whip Abdus Shahid, Suranjit Sengupta, Tofail Ahmed, Sheikh Fazlul Karim Selim, Abdul Matin Khasru, Ali Ashraf, Fazle Rabbi Mian, Obaidul Quader, Hafiz Uddin Ahmmad, Shirin Sharmin Chowdhury and Rehana Akhter Ranu Abdul Hamid will also head the petition committee. Its other members are: Mojibul Haq, A B M Ruhul Amin Howlader, Md Amanullah, Mozammel Hossain, Habibur Rahman, Mollah, Kamal Ahmed Majumder, Motiur Rahman, Shahiduzzamn Sarker and Nazrul Islam Manju. Former law minister Abdul Matin Khasru heads the committee on private members' bills and private members' resolutions. A S M Feroz, Shajahan Khan, Mahbubur Rahman, Moslem Uddin, Mohibur Rhman Manik, Abdul Hye, Nurul Mazid MAhmud Humayun, Iqbalur Rahim and Syeda Asifa Ashrafi Papiya are the other members of the committee. Deputy speaker Col Shawkat Ali will head the library committee. Other members are: Abdul Wahab, Imran Ahmed, Ishak Hossain Talukder, Kazi Keramat Ali, Shah Alam, Meher Afroz, Z A Russel, Begum Mahbub Ara Gini and Shammi Akhter. K H Rashiduzzaman has been elected chairman of the public accounts committee. Others members are: Khan Tipu Sultan, TIM Fazle Rabbi Chowdhury, Ali Ashraf, Imaz Uddin Pramanik, Chhayedul Haq, Enamul Haq, A K M Rahmatulla, Khandker Asaduzzaman, Dhirendra Devnath Shambhu, Abdus Salam, Hafiz Ahmed Majumder, Salahuddin Quader Chowdhury, M K Anwar and Farid Akhter. Mohiuddin Khan Alamgir will head the committee on public undertaking. TIM Fazle Rabbi Chowdhury, Khalidur Rahman Tito, Dhirendra Devnath Shambhu, Biren Shiklder, Moinuddin Khan Badal, S K Abu Baker, Bazlul Haq Harun, Zaiunl Abdin Farroque and Amina Ahmed are the other members. Fazle Rabbi Mian has been elected chairman of the parliamentary standing committee on government assurances. Other members are: Abdul Quddus, Dabirul Islam, Ekabbar Hjossain, Mujibur Rahman Fakir, B M Mozammel, Khalid Mahmud Chowdury and Rashida Begum Hira. Idris Ali will head parliamentary standing committee on defence ministry. The other members are: Sheikh Hasina, H M Ershad, Muhammad Jamiruddin Sircr, Eng Mosharraf Hossain, Mojiubl Haq, Sheikh Helal Uddin, Nurul Majid Mahmud Humayun, Rafiqul Islam and Monjur Qauder Quraishi. A B M Fazle Karim Chowdhury has been elected chairman of the parliamentary standing committee on housing and public works. Abdul Mannan Khan, Noor-e-